e8h\u00e9\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u71b1}}</span>||R\u00e8\n|[[Chengde|Chengteh]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u627f\u5fb7}}</span>||Ch\u00e9ngd\u00e9\n|1914 created from Inner Mongolia\n|-\n|[[Xikang|Sikang]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u897f\u5eb7}}</span>||X\u012bk\u0101ng\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5eb7}}</span>||K\u0101ng\n|[[Kangding|Kangting]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5eb7\u5b9a}}</span>||K\u0101ngd\u00ecng\n|1925 renamed from Chwanpien\n|-\n|[[Suiyuan]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u7d8f\u9060}}</span>||Su\u012byu\u01cen\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u7d8f}}</span>||Su\u012b\n|[[Hohhot|Kweisui]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u6b78\u7d8f}}</span>||Gu\u012bsu\u012b\n|1913 created from Inner Mongolia<br>Kweisui was renamed [[Hohhot]] (\u547c\u548c\u6d69\u7279) after 1949\n|-\n|Tungsheng||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u6771\u7701}}</span>||D\u014dngsh\u011bng\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u6771\u7701}}</span>||D\u014dngsh\u011bng\n|[[Harbin]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u54c8\u723e\u6ff1}}</span>||H\u0101'\u011brb\u012bn\n|Land along the [[Chinese Eastern Railway]], spanned from [[Manzhouli]] through [[Harbin]] to [[Suifenhe]].\n|-\n! colspan=9 style=\"background:#ffff99;\" | Commercial Region (<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5546\u57e0}}</span> ''Sh\u0101ngb\u00f9'')\n|- bgcolor=#f5c3c4\n|Kiao-ao||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u81a0\u6fb3}}</span>||Ji\u0101o'\u00e0o\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u81a0}}</span>||Ji\u0101o\n|[[Qingdao|Tsingtao]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u9752\u5cf6}}</span>||Q\u012bngd\u01ceo\n|Formerly Japanese and German [[Concessions in China|concession]].<br>1925 abolished \u2192 Shantung\n|- bgcolor=lightblue\n|Sunghu||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u6dde\u6eec}}</span>||S\u014dngh\u00f9\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u6eec}}</span>||H\u00f9\n|[[Shanghai]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u4e0a\u6d77}}</span>||Sh\u00e0ngh\u01cei\n|Status in dispute. Division established by the [[Zhili clique]] leader [[Sun Chuanfang]], was not recognized by the central government.\n|}\n\n== Nationalist Government (1928\u201349) ==\n{|\n|[[File:China in 1936.svg|thumb|250px|Map of the Republic of China in 1936]]\n|[[File:China in 1946.svg|thumb|250px|Map of the Republic of China in 1946]]\n|[[File:China in 1949.svg|thumb|250px|Map of the Republic of China in 1949]]\n|}\n\nThe [[Nationalist Government]] also began setting up [[Municipalities of China|municipalities]], cities directly administered by the central government. More levels began to be added below the county, [[Townships of China|townships]] for instance. Circuits were then abolished in 1928 as being superfluous. However, this reform was soon found to be unfeasible since the average province now had 50+ counties and some more than a hundred. As a result, some provinces were later subdivided into several prefectures.\n\n* [[Provinces of China|Provinces]] (\u7701, ''sh\u011bng'')\n** Administrative superintendent district (\u884c\u653f\u7763\u5bdf\u5340, ''x\u00edngzh\u00e8ng d\u016bch\u00e1q\u016b'')\n* [[Counties of China|Counties]] (\u7e23, ''xi\u00e0n'')\n\nThe creation of the [[puppet state]] [[Manchukuo]] by the [[Empire of Japan]] in the 1930s deprived China of 4 provinces in the northeast ([[Liaoning|Fengtien]], [[Heilongjiang|Heilungkiang]], [[Jehol Province|Jehol]], [[Jilin|Kirin]]). After the defeat of [[Japan]] in 1945, [[Manchuria]] was reincorporated into China as 9 provinces and 3 municipalities. The [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]] also annexed [[Taiwan]] and the [[Pescadores]] and organized into [[Taiwan Province]]. By this time there was a total of thirty-five provinces, twelve municipalities  (\u9662\u8f44\u5e02, ''yu\u00e0nxi\u00e1sh\u00ec''), one special administrative region (\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340, ''t\u00e8bi\u00e9 x\u00edngzh\u00e8ngq\u01d6''), and two regions (\u5730\u65b9, ''dif\u0101ng'') as first-level divisions under the Republic of China.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|+Administrative divisions of the Republic of China (1928\u20131949)\n!colspan=3|Division name!!colspan=2|Abbreviation!!colspan=3|Capital name!!rowspan=2 width=350|Note\n|-\n![[Postal romanization|Postal]]!![[Chinese character|Chinese]]!![[Pinyin]]\n![[Chinese character|Chinese]]!![[Pinyin]]\n![[Postal romanization|Postal]]!![[Chinese character|Chinese]]!![[Pinyin]]\n|-\n! colspan=9 style=\"background:#ffff99;\" | Provinces (<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u7701}}</span> ''Sh\u011bng'')\n|-\n|[[Andong Province|Antung]] || <span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5b89\u6771}}</span> || \u0100nd\u014dng\n| <span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5b89}}</span> || \u0100n\n|[[Tonghua|Tunghwa]] || <span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u901a\u5316}}</span> || T\u014dnghu\u00e0\n|1947 created from [[Manchukuo]] (originally part of Liaoning)\n|-\n|[[Anhui|Anhwei]] || <span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5b89\u5fbd}}</span> || \u0100nhu\u012b\n| <span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u7696}}</span> || W\u01cen\n|[[Hefei|Hofei]] || <span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5408\u80a5}}</span> || H\u00e9f\u00e9i ||\n|-\n|[[Chahar Province|Chahar]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5bdf\u54c8\u723e}}</span>||Ch\u00e1h\u0101\u011br\n|<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5bdf}}</span>||Ch\u00e1\n|[[Zhangjiakou|Kalgan]]||<span style=\"font-size:125%;\">{{lang|zh-hant|\u5f35\u57a3}}</span>||Zh\u0101ngyu\u00e1n\n|1928 reformed from a special administrative region<br>Kalgan was renamed [[Zhangjiakou]] (\u5f35\u5bb6\u53e3) after 1949.\n|-\n|[[Zhejiang|Chekiang]] || <span 