n Green Elementary School, Bel Air\n*George D. Lisby Elementary School at Hillsdale, Aberdeen\n*Hall's Cross Roads Elementary School, Aberdeen\n*Havre de Grace Elementary School, [[Havre de Grace, Maryland|Havre de Grace]]\n*Hickory Elementary School, Bel Air\n*Homestead/Wakefield Elementary School, Bel Air\n*Jarrettsville Elementary School, [[Jarrettsville, Maryland|Jarrettsville]]\n*Joppatowne Elementary School, [[Joppa, Maryland|Joppa]]\n*Magnolia Elementary School, Joppa\n*Meadowvale Elementary School, Havre de Grace\n*Norrisville Elementary School, [[White Hall, Baltimore County, Maryland|White Hall]]\n*North Bend Elementary School, Jarrettsville\n*North Harford Elementary School, [[Pylesville, Maryland|Pylesville]]\n*Prospect Mill Elementary School, Bel Air\n*Red Pump Elementary School, Bel Air\n*Ring Factory Elementary School, Bel Air\n*Riverside Elementary School, Joppa\n*Roye-Williams Elementary School, Havre de Grace\n*William Paca/Old Post Road Elementary School, Abingdon\n*William S. James Elementary School, Abingdon\n*Youth's Benefit Elementary School, [[Fallston, Maryland|Fallston]]\n\n===Middle schools===\nThere are currently 9 middle schools in Harford County:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcps.org/Schools/Middle/Default.aspx|title=Middle Schools|website=Hcps.org|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Aberdeen Middle School]], Aberdeen\n*[[Bel Air Middle School]], Bel Air\n*Edgewood Middle School, Edgewood\n*Fallston Middle School, Fallston\n*Havre de Grace Middle School, Havre de Grace\n*Magnolia Middle School, Joppa\n*North Harford Middle School, Pylesville\n*[[Patterson Mill Middle/High School]], Bel Air\n*Southampton Middle School, Bel Air\n\n===High schools===\nThere are currently ten high schools in Harford County, including one technical high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcps.org/Schools/High/Default.aspx|title=High Schools|website=Hcps.org|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Aberdeen High School (Aberdeen, Maryland)|Aberdeen High School]], Aberdeen\n*[[Bel Air High School (Bel Air, Maryland)|Bel Air High School]], Bel Air\n*[[C. Milton Wright High School]], Bel Air\n*[[Edgewood High School (Edgewood, Maryland)|Edgewood High School]], Edgewood\n*[[Fallston High School]], Fallston\n*[[Harford Technical High School]], Bel Air\n*[[Havre De Grace High School|Havre de Grace High School]], Havre de Grace\n*[[Joppatowne High School]], Joppa\n*[[North Harford High School]], Pylesville\n*[[Patterson Mill Middle/High School]], Bel Air\n\n'''High School Advanced Placement Scores 2015'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://reportcard.msde.maryland.gov/rschool.aspx?K=03AAAA&WDATA=school |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-09-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912061159/http://reportcard.msde.maryland.gov/rschool.aspx?K=03AAAA&WDATA=school |archive-date=2016-09-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! High School !! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 100px;\" | High School Enrollment !! AP Exams !! AP Exams 3+ !! AP Exams 3+ %\n|-\n| Aberdeen || 1444 || 658 || 488 || 74.2%\n|-\n| Bel Air || 1668 || 550 || 318 || 57.8%\n|-\n| C. Milton Wright || 1425 || 564 || 430 || 76.2%\n|-\n| Edgewood || 1318|| 189 || 65 || 32.80%\n|-\n| Fallston || 1076 || 589 || 360 || 61.1%\n|-\n| Harford Tech || 1022 || 230 || 90 || 39.0%\n|-\n| Havre de Grace || 581 || 245 || 85 || 34.7%\n|-\n| Joppatowne || 696 || 139 || 41 || 29.5%\n|-\n| North Harford || 1297 || 402 || 270 || 67.2%\n|-\n| Patterson Mill || 871 || 314 || 203 || 64.6%\n|}\n\n====Magnet programs====\nThree HCPS high schools also have or are preparing for [[magnet school|magnet programs]]. Although the Science and Mathematics Academy is a separate institution, it is hosted by and shares some facilities with [[Aberdeen High School (Aberdeen, Maryland)|Aberdeen High School]], and [[Harford Technical High School]] is in itself a magnet school for academic and technical programs. [[Edgewood High School (Edgewood, Maryland)|Edgewood High School]] is in the beginning stages of the [[IB Diploma Programme|International Baccalaureate Diploma Programme]], in which the school will offer college-preparatory courses for its students, who will graduate with an internationally recognized high school diploma. Edgewood also offers the Academy of Finance program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcps.org/Schools/MagnetPrograms/Default.aspx|title=Harford County Public Schools Magnet Programs|website=Hcps.org|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n*Academy of Finance at Edgewood High School\n*Harford Technical High School in [[Bel Air, Maryland]]\n*Homeland Security at Joppatowne High School\n*International Baccalaureate at Edgewood High School\n*Natural Resources and Agricultural Science Magnet Program at North Harford High School\n*Science and Mathematics Academy at Aberdeen High School\n\n====Mascots====\nThe school mascots are:\n*Aberdeen Eagles\n*Bel Air Bobcats\n*C. Milton Wright Mustangs\n*Edgewood Rams\n*Fallston Cougars\n*Harford Technical Cobras\n*Havre de Grace Warriors\n*Joppatowne Mariners\n*North Harford Hawks\n*Patterson Mill Huskies\n\n===Alternative/charter schools===\n*John Archer School, Bel Air,'' grades K-8''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcps.org/Schools/Alternative/Default.aspx|title=Alternative Schools|website=Hcps.org|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==School feeder systems==\nThe images below outline the elementary and middle schools that feed students into each high school. Harford Technical is fed by students from each school, as entry is by application. The feeder system is not all-inclusive, due to magnet programs at Aberdeen, Edgewood, and Joppatowne.\n<gallery widths=105>\nImage:AberdeenFeeder.png|'''Aberdeen'''\nImage:BelAirFeeder.png|'''Bel Air'''\nImage:CMiltonFeeder.png|'''C. Milton Wright'''\nImage:EdgewoodFeeder.png|'''Edgewood'''\nImage:FallstonFeeder.png|'''Fallston'''\nImage:HDGFeeder.png|'''Havre de Grace'''\nImage:JoppaFeeder.png|'''Joppatowne'''\nImage:NHarfordFeeder.png|'''North Harford'''\nImage:PMillFeeder.png|'''Patterson Mill'''\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Harford Glen Environmental Education Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hcps.org/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100615214618/http://hcps.org/aboutus/docs/minifacts.pdf Facts about HCPS]\n*[http://www.hcps.org/schools/schoolprofiles.aspx HCPS district profile]\n*[http://members.thinkport.org/ucbac Upper Chesapeake Bay Athletic Conference]\n\n{{Harford County Public Schools}}\n\n[[Category:School districts in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Education in Harford County, Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "100.16.31.139", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Dhej)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harford_County_Public_Schools"}
{"title_page": "Nikolai Basistiy", "text_new": "{{short description|Soviet naval officer}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Nikolai Efremovich Basistiy\n| birth_date    = {{OldStyleDate|22 May|1898|10 May}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|10|20|1898|5|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = {{ill|Yurevka|ru|\u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043a\u0430 (\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d)}}, {{ill|Elisavetgradskii Uezd|ru|\u0415\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u0435\u0437\u0434}}, [[Kherson Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_place   = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| placeofburial = [[Novodevichy Cemetery]]\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|Russian Empire}}<br>{{USSR}}\n| branch        = {{navy|Russian Empire}}<br>{{navy|USSR}}\n| serviceyears  = 1914-1960\n| rank          = [[Admiral]]\n| commands      = [[Black Sea Fleet]]\n| battles       = \n| awards        = [[Imperial Russia]]\n*{{ill|St. George Medal|ru|\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c}}\n[[Soviet Union]]\n*[[Order of Lenin]] (twice)\n*[[Order of the Red Banner]] (four times)\n*[[Order of Ushakov]] Second Class\n*[[Order of Kutuzov]] Second Class\nForeign Awards\n*[[Navy Cross]] (USA)\n| laterwork     = \n}}\n\n'''Nikolai Efremovich Basistiy''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439}}) ({{OldStyleDate|22 May|1898|10 May}} &ndash; 20 October 1971) was an officer of the [[Soviet Navy]]. He rose to the rank of admiral and was commander of the [[Black Sea Fleet]], in a career that spanned the [[First World War|First]] and [[Second World War]]s, and the [[Russian Civil War]].\n\nBorn into a peasant family, Basistiy served as a mine specialist during the First World War, being decorated for his service in the Black Sea Fleet. Continuing his naval career after the [[Russian Revolution]], Basistiy became a supporter of the Bolsheviks, and served in the [[Soviet Navy|Workers' and Peasants' Red Fleet]] during the Russian Civil War. He saw action against the [[White movement]] and other anti-Bolshevik risings in [[Odessa]] and [[Astrakhan]], and as part of the {{ill|Volga military flotilla (Russian Civil War)|ru|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f (\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0430)|lt=Volga}} and {{ill|Caspian military flotilla|ru|\u041a\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f|lt=Caspian military flotillas}}. With the Bolshevik victory in the civil war, Basistiy undertook various studies and specialised in mine warfare. He was sent to serve as an advisor to the [[Spanish Republican Navy]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]], and was decorated for his service.\n\nHe served with distinction in the Black Sea during the Second World War, at first as commander of a cruiser, and then rising to the post of chief of staff, and for a time acting fleet commander. He saw action at many of the defensive operations during the sieges of Soviet Black Sea ports, and at the landing operations to force enemy invaders back. Shortly after the war he became commander in chief of the Black Sea Fleet. Towards the end of his career he was a deputy to [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]], and an advisor to the Group of Inspectors General of the [[Ministry of Defense (Soviet Union)|Ministry of Defence]], before his retirement in 1960. He wrote his memoirs, which were published shortly before his death in 1971.\n\n==Early career==\nBasistiy was born to a peasant family on {{OldStyleDate|22 May|1898|10 May}} in the village of {{ill|Yurevka|ru|\u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043a\u0430 (\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d)}}, {{ill|Elisavetgradskii Uezd|ru|\u0415\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u0435\u0437\u0434}}, in the [[Kherson Governorate]], which was at that time part of the [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite book|first=Nikolai|last=Skritskiy|title=\u0424\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043c\u0430\u043d\u044b \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b. \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0438 \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0442\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b 1941\u20131945|language=Russian|publisher=Litres|year=2017|isbn=9785457227477}}</ref> He entered the military with the outbreak of the [[First World War]], graduating from the [[Junker (Russia)|junker]] school in [[Sevastopol]] in 1915, and in 1916 entered the [[Black Sea Fleet]]'s mine school. After time aboard the [[training ship]] ''Rion'', he served in the fleet as a non-commissioned mine officer second class aboard the destroyers ''Zharky'' and ''Sulin''. He was awarded the {{ill|St. George Medal|ru|\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c}} and promoted to mine officer first class in autumn 1916.<ref name=\"FP\"/><ref name=\"TN\">{{cite web|url=https://timenote.info/ru/Nikolaj-Basistij|title=\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439|language=Russian|website=timenote.info|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBasistiy continued in naval service during the [[Russian Revolution]], being elected to the ''Zharky''{{'}}s ship committee in February 1917 and serving in the [[Soviet Navy|Workers' and Peasants' Red Fleet]] from 1918 onwards.<ref name=\"FP\"/>  He took part in the [[Russian Civil War]], at first aboard the ''Zharky'' where he participated in the suppression of the [[Haidamaka]] rising in [[Odessa]], and then as a signalman aboard the artillery barge ''Serezha'', around[[Nizhny Novgorod]]. He then served aboard the gun boat ''Krasnoye Znamya'' with the {{ill|Volga military flotilla (Russian Civil War)|ru|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f (\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0430)|lt=Volga military flotilla}} in the [[Tsaritsyn]] area.<ref name=\"FP\"/>  Here he fought against the troops of the [[White movement]], led by Generals [[Anton Denikin]] and [[Pyotr Krasnov]]. Basistiy then served in the {{ill|Caspian military flotilla|ru|\u041a\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f|lt=Caspian military flotilla}}, helping to suppress the anti-Bolshevik uprising in [[Astrakhan]].<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==Soviet Navy service==\nAfter the Bolshevik victory in the Civil War, Basistiy attended the [[Sverdlov Communist University]] in Moscow from October 1921 to August 1922, and served from August 1922 to October 1926 in various administrative posts in different parts of the Navy.<ref name=\"FP\"/> He attended the [[N. G. Kuznetsov Naval Academy|Naval Academy]], graduating in 1931 and from March 1931 to April 1932 worked as an adjunct in the Naval Academy.<ref name=\"TN\"/> From April 1932 to March 1934 Basistiy was chief of staff of the minesweeping forces, and from March 1934 to October 1936 was chief of the combat training department at the [[Pacific Fleet (Russia)|Pacific Fleet]] headquarters. Basistiy then went to Spain from April 1937 to July 1938, during the [[Spanish Civil War]], where he served as an adviser to the commander of the [[Spanish Republican Navy]].<ref name=\"TN\"/> The Soviets awarded him the [[Order of the Red Banner]] for his service in Spain. He completed a course of studies at the [[Military Academy of the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Russia|Military Academy of the General Staff]] and from July 1938 to October 1939 was the Black Sea Fleet's chief of operations.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==The Second World War==\n[[File:Krasnaya Ukraina.jpg|thumb|right|The cruiser [[Soviet cruiser Chervona Ukraina|''Chervona Ukraina'']], Basistiy's ship from 1939 until 1941]]\nOctober 1939 Basistiy took command of the cruiser [[Soviet cruiser Chervona Ukraina|''Chervona Ukraina'']], and was her captain at the [[Operation Barbarossa|German invasion of the Soviet Union]] in 1941. Basistiy was transferred to command the Black Sea Fleet's Light Squadron in November 1941, holding the post until July 1942.<ref name=\"ve\">{{cite web|url=https://pamyat-naroda.ru/commander/80/|title=\u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|language=Russian|website=pamyat-naroda.ru|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> During this time he assisted in the [[Kerch-Feodosiya landing operation]] in December 1941-January 1942.<ref name=\"TN\"/> From July 1942 to March 1943 he was commander of the Black Sea Fleet's cruiser squadron, taking part in the {{ill|Siege of Novorossiysk|ru|\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f (1942)|lt=defence of Novorossiysk}}.<ref name=\"TN\"/> He was temporarily the fleet's chief of staff from April to May 1943, after which he once more commanded a squadron of the fleet. He was once more chief of staff of the fleet from November 1944 to November 1948, with a brief period from January to April 1945 when he was acting commander of the Black Sea Fleet.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==Postwar==\nBasistiy was commander of the Black Sea Fleet from November 1948 to August 1951, after which he became First Deputy Naval Minister of the USSR, until April 1953. From April 1953 to November 1956 he served as First Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the Navy, and from November 1956 to June 1958 was Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the Navy for military research. From 1952 to 1956 he was a candidate member of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]], and was a Deputy of the [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]]  at its 3rd and 4th convocation sessions, from 1950 to 1954 and 1954 to 1958 respectively. Basistiy's last posting was as Advisor to the Group of Inspectors General of the [[Ministry of Defense (Soviet Union)|Ministry of Defence]], from June 1958 to September 1960.<ref name=\"TN\"/> Basistiy retired in September 1960, and in retirement wrote accounts of his service.<ref name=\"TN\"/> Over his career he was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]] twice, in 1942 and 1945; the [[Order of the Red Banner]] four times, in 1937, 1944, 1945, and 1948; the [[Order of Ushakov]] Second Class in 1944; and the [[Order of Kutuzov]] Second Class in 1945. He was also awarded the [[Navy Cross]] from the United States of America in 1943.<ref name=\"FP\"/> Basistiy died in Moscow on 20 October 1971, and was buried in the [[Novodevichy Cemetery]].<ref name=\"FP\"/><ref name=\"np\">{{cite web|url=http://nd.m-necropol.ru/basistiy-ne.html|title=\u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (1898-1971)|language=Russian|website=necropol.ru|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> His wife, Tamara Iosifovna, had predeceased him in 1960 and they were buried side by side. In 2011 their daughter, Elena Nikolaevna, was interred in the same plot.<ref name=\"nn\">{{cite web|url=http://novodevichiynecropol.narod.ru/08/basistiy_ne.htm|title= \u0411\u0410\u0421\u0418\u0421\u0422\u042b\u0419 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (1898\u20131971)|language=Russian|website=novodevichiynecropol|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> The Soviet Navy planned to honour Basistiy by naming an [[Udaloy-class destroyer|''Udaloy II''-class destroyer]] ''Admiral Basistiy''. She was laid down in 1991, but the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] later that year interrupted her building, and she was scrapped on the slipway in 1994.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Basistiy , N. E., ''Battles with the White Guards and the Interventionists on the Volga (1918-1919)'' ({{Lang-ru|\u0431\u043e\u044f\u0445 \u0441 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0446\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0435 (1918\u20141919 \u0433\u0433.) }}, ''Boyakh c Belogvardeitsami i interventami na Volge (1918-1919 gg.''), ''Morskoi Sbornik'' (1968). \u2116 2. pp.&nbsp;25\u201331.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n*Basistiy , N. E., ''Sea and Shore'' ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u0438 \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0433}}, ''More i bereg''), (1970) Moscow, [[Voenizdat]].<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n*Basistiy , N. E., ''Unforgettable Happenings'' ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0431\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0435 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442}}, ''Nezabymaemoe budaet''), (1970) Moscow. 1970. No. 5. pp.&nbsp;171\u2013172.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FAG|106154382}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basistiy, Nikolai}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Novodevichy Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Kherson Governorate]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:Soviet admirals]]\n[[Category:Soviet historians]]\n[[Category:Russian military writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:Russian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Soviet military personnel of the Russian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Soviet military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Kutuzov, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ushakov, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Red Banner]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Soviet naval officer}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Nikolai Efremovich Basistiy\n| birth_date    = {{OldStyleDate|22 May|1898|10 May}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|10|20|1898|5|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = {{ill|Yurevka|ru|\u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043a\u0430 (\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d)}}, {{ill|Elisavetgradskii Uezd|ru|\u0415\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u0435\u0437\u0434}}, [[Kherson Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_place   = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| placeofburial = [[Novodevichy Cemetery]]\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|Russian Empire}}<br>{{USSR}}\n| branch        = {{navy|Russian Empire}}<br>{{navy|USSR}}\n| serviceyears  = 1914-1960\n| rank          = [[Admiral]]\n| commands      = [[Black Sea Fleet]]\n| battles       = \n| awards        = [[Imperial Russia]]\n*{{ill|St. George Medal|ru|\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c}}\n[[Soviet Union]]\n*[[Order of Lenin]] (twice)\n*[[Order of the Red Banner]] (four times)\n*[[Order of Ushakov]] Second Class\n*[[Order of Kutuzov]] Second Class\nForeign Awards\n*[[Navy Cross]] (USA)\n| laterwork     = \n}}\n\n'''Nikolai Efremovich Basistiy''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439}}) ({{OldStyleDate|22 May|1898|10 May}} &ndash; 20 October 1971) was an officer of the [[Soviet Navy]]. He rose to the rank of admiral and was commander of the [[Black Sea Fleet]], in a career that spanned the [[First World War|First]] and [[Second World War]]s, and the [[Russian Civil War]].\n\nBorn into a peasant family, Basistiy served as a mine specialist during the First World War, being decorated for his service in the Black Sea Fleet. Continuing his naval career after the [[Russian Revolution]], Basistiy became a supporter of the Bolsheviks, and served in the [[Soviet Navy|Workers' and Peasants' Red Fleet]] during the Russian Civil War. He saw action against the [[White movement]] and other anti-Bolshevik risings in [[Odessa]] and [[Astrakhan]], and as part of the {{ill|Volga military flotilla (Russian Civil War)|ru|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f (\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0430)|lt=Volga}} and {{ill|Caspian military flotilla|ru|\u041a\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f|lt=Caspian military flotillas}}. With the Bolshevik victory in the civil war, Basistiy undertook various studies and specialised in mine warfare. He was sent to serve as an advisor to the [[Spanish Republican Navy]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]], and was decorated for his service.\n\nHe served with distinction in the Black Sea during the Second World War, at first as commander of a cruiser, and then rising to the post of chief of staff, and for a time acting fleet commander. He saw action at many of the defensive operations during the sieges of Soviet Black Sea ports, and at the landing operations to force enemy invaders back. Shortly after the war he became commander in chief of the Black Sea Fleet. Towards the end of his career he was a deputy to [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]], and an advisor to the Group of Inspectors General of the [[Ministry of Defense (Soviet Union)|Ministry of Defence]], before his retirement in 1960. He wrote his memoirs, which were published shortly before his death in 1971.\n\n==Early career==\nBasistiy was born to a peasant family on {{OldStyleDate|22 May|1898|10 May}} in the village of {{ill|Yurevka|ru|\u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043a\u0430 (\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d)}}, {{ill|Elisavetgradskii Uezd|ru|\u0415\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u0435\u0437\u0434}}, in the [[Kherson Governorate]], which was at that time part of the [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite book|first=Nikolai|last=Skritskiy|title=\u0424\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043c\u0430\u043d\u044b \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b. \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0438 \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0442\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b 1941\u20131945|language=Russian|publisher=Litres|year=2017|isbn=9785457227477}}</ref> He entered the military with the outbreak of the [[First World War]], graduating from the [[Junker (Russia)|junker]] school in [[Sevastopol]] in 1915, and in 1916 entered the [[Black Sea Fleet]]'s mine school. After time aboard the [[training ship]] ''Rion'', he served in the fleet as a non-commissioned mine officer second class aboard the destroyers ''Zharky'' and ''Sulin''. He was awarded the {{ill|St. George Medal|ru|\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c}} and promoted to mine officer first class in autumn 1916.<ref name=\"FP\"/><ref name=\"TN\">{{cite web|url=https://timenote.info/ru/Nikolaj-Basistij|title=\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439|language=Russian|website=timenote.info|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBasistiy continued in naval service during the [[Russian Revolution]], being elected to the ''Zharky''{{'}}s ship committee in February 1917 and serving in the [[Soviet Navy|Workers' and Peasants' Red Fleet]] from 1918 onwards.<ref name=\"FP\"/>  He took part in the [[Russian Civil War]], at first aboard the ''Zharky'' where he participated in the suppression of the [[Haidamaka]] rising in [[Odessa]], and then as a signalman aboard the artillery barge ''Serezha'', around[[Nizhny Novgorod]]. He then served aboard the gun boat ''Krasnoye Znamya'' with the {{ill|Volga military flotilla (Russian Civil War)|ru|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f (\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0430)|lt=Volga military flotilla}} in the [[Tsaritsyn]] area.<ref name=\"FP\"/>  Here he fought against the troops of the [[White movement]], led by Generals [[Anton Denikin]] and [[Pyotr Krasnov]]. Basistiy then served in the {{ill|Caspian military flotilla|ru|\u041a\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f|lt=Caspian military flotilla}}, helping to suppress the anti-Bolshevik uprising in [[Astrakhan]].<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==Soviet Navy service==\nAfter the Bolshevik victory in the Civil War, Basistiy attended the [[Sverdlov Communist University]] in Moscow from October 1921 to August 1922, and served from August 1922 to October 1926 in various administrative posts in different parts of the Navy.<ref name=\"FP\"/> He attended the [[N. G. Kuznetsov Naval Academy|Naval Academy]], graduating in 1931 and from March 1931 to April 1932 worked as an adjunct in the Naval Academy.<ref name=\"TN\"/> From April 1932 to March 1934 Basistiy was chief of staff of the minesweeping forces, and from March 1934 to October 1936 was chief of the combat training department at the [[Pacific Fleet (Russia)|Pacific Fleet]] headquarters. Basistiy then went to Spain from April 1937 to July 1938, during the [[Spanish Civil War]], where he served as an adviser to the commander of the [[Spanish Republican Navy]].<ref name=\"TN\"/> The Soviets awarded him the [[Order of the Red Banner]] for his service in Spain. He completed a course of studies at the [[Military Academy of the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Russia|Military Academy of the General Staff]] and from July 1938 to October 1939 was the Black Sea Fleet's chief of operations.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==The Second World War==\n[[File:Krasnaya Ukraina.jpg|thumb|right|The cruiser [[Soviet cruiser Chervona Ukraina|''Chervona Ukraina'']], Basistiy's ship from 1939 until 1941]]\nOctober 1939 Basistiy took command of the cruiser [[Soviet cruiser Chervona Ukraina|''Chervona Ukraina'']], and was her captain at the [[Operation Barbarossa|German invasion of the Soviet Union]] in 1941. Basistiy was transferred to command the Black Sea Fleet's Light Squadron in November 1941, holding the post until July 1942.<ref name=\"ve\">{{cite web|url=https://pamyat-naroda.ru/commander/80/|title=\u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|language=Russian|website=pamyat-naroda.ru|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> During this time he assisted in the [[Kerch-Feodosiya landing operation]] in December 1941-January 1942.<ref name=\"TN\"/> From July 1942 to March 1943 he was commander of the Black Sea Fleet's cruiser squadron, taking part in the {{ill|Siege of Novorossiysk|ru|\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f (1942)|lt=defence of Novorossiysk}}.<ref name=\"TN\"/> He was temporarily the fleet's chief of staff from April to May 1943, after which he once more commanded a squadron of the fleet. He was once more chief of staff of the fleet from November 1944 to November 1948, with a brief period from January to April 1945 when he was acting commander of the Black Sea Fleet.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==Postwar==\nBasistiy was commander of the Black Sea Fleet from November 1948 to August 1951, after which he became First Deputy Naval Minister of the USSR, until April 1953. From April 1953 to November 1956 he served as First Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the Navy, and from November 1956 to June 1958 was Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the Navy for military research. From 1952 to 1956 he was a candidate member of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]], and was a Deputy of the [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]]  at its 3rd and 4th convocation sessions, from 1950 to 1954 and 1954 to 1958 respectively. Basistiy's last posting was as Advisor to the Group of Inspectors General of the [[Ministry of Defense (Soviet Union)|Ministry of Defence]], from June 1958 to September 1960.<ref name=\"TN\"/> Basistiy retired in September 1960, and in retirement wrote accounts of his service.<ref name=\"TN\"/> Over his career he was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]] twice, in 1942 and 1945; the [[Order of the Red Banner]] four times, in 1937, 1944, 1945, and 1948; the [[Order of Ushakov]] Second Class in 1944; and the [[Order of Kutuzov]] Second Class in 1945. He was also awarded the [[Navy Cross]] from the United States of America in 1943.<ref name=\"FP\"/> Basistiy died in Moscow on 20 October 1971, and was buried in the [[Novodevichy Cemetery]].<ref name=\"FP\"/><ref name=\"np\">{{cite web|url=http://nd.m-necropol.ru/basistiy-ne.html|title=\u0411\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (1898-1971)|language=Russian|website=necropol.ru|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> His wife, Tamara Iosifovna, had predeceased him in 1960 and they were buried side by side. In 2011 their daughter, Elena Nikolaevna, was interred in the same plot.<ref name=\"nn\">{{cite web|url=http://novodevichiynecropol.narod.ru/08/basistiy_ne.htm|title= \u0411\u0410\u0421\u0418\u0421\u0422\u042b\u0419 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0415\u0444\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (1898\u20131971)|language=Russian|website=novodevichiynecropol|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> The Soviet Navy planned to honour Basistiy by naming an [[Udaloy-class destroyer|''Udaloy II''-class destroyer]] ''Admiral Basistiy''. She was laid down in 1991, but the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] later that year interrupted her building, and she was scrapped on the slipway in 1994.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Basistiy , N. E., ''Battles with the White Guards and the Interventionists on the Volga (1918-1919)'' ({{Lang-ru|\u0431\u043e\u044f\u0445 \u0441 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0446\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0435 (1918\u20141919 \u0433\u0433.) }}, ''Boyakh c Belogvardeitsami i interventami na Volge (1918-1919 gg.''), ''Morskoi Sbornik'' (1968). \u2116 2. pp. 25-31.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n*Basistiy , N. E., ''Sea and Shore'' ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u0438 \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0433}}, ''More i bereg''), (1970) Moscow, [[Voenizdat]].<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n*Basistiy , N. E., ''Unforgettable Happenings'' ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0431\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0435 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442}}, ''Nezabymaemoe budaet''), (1970) Moscow. 1970. No. 5. pp. 171-172.<ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{FAG|106154382}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basistiy, Nikolai}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Novodevichy Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Kherson Governorate]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:Soviet admirals]]\n[[Category:Soviet historians]]\n[[Category:Russian military writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:Russian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Soviet military personnel of the Russian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Soviet military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Kutuzov, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ushakov, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Red Banner]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikolai_Basistiy"}
